{"title_page": "Responses to the COVID-19 pandemic in May 2020", "text_new": "{{See also|COVID-19 pandemic|Timeline of the COVID-19 pandemic in May 2020}}\n{{short description|Sequence of major events in a virus pandemic}}\n{{Main|Timeline of the COVID-19 pandemic}}\n{{EngvarB|date=April 2020}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Expand list|date=April 2020}}\n{{COVID-19 pandemic sidebar |expanded=timeline}}\n\nThis article documents the chronology of the response to the [[COVID-19 pandemic]] in May 2020, which originated in [[Wuhan]], China in December 2019. Some developments may become known or fully understood only in retrospect. Reporting on this pandemic began in [[Timeline of the COVID-19 pandemic from November to December 2019|December 2019]].\n{{TOC limit}}\n\n== Reactions and measures in Africa ==\n===1 May===\nSouth Africa has begun to loosen its lockdown restrictions, allowing some businesses including winter clothing, textile, and packaging factories to resume operations. Restaurants will be allowed to provide takeaway services. Recreational activities such as walking, cycling, and running will be allowed for three hours a day. The South African Government has maintained a ban on the sales of cigarettes and alcohol.<ref name=\"Al Jazeera 1 May reports\">{{cite news |last1=Regencia |first1=Ted |last2=Aziz |first2=Saba |last3=Stepansky |first3=Joseph |title=WHO says coronavirus 'natural in origin': Live updates |url=https://www.aljazeera.com/news/2020/04/trump-suggests-coronavirus-linked-wuhan-lab-live-updates-200430231206079.html |accessdate=1 May 2020 |work=[[Al Jazeera]] |date=1 May 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200501224421/https://www.aljazeera.com/news/2020/04/trump-suggests-coronavirus-linked-wuhan-lab-live-updates-200430231206079.html|archive-date=1 May 2020}}</ref>\n\n[[President of Zimbabwe]] [[Emmerson Mnangagwa]] has extended Zimbabwe's lockdown for two more weeks and announced a US$720 million stimulus for affected companies.<ref name=\"Al Jazeera 1 May reports\" />\n\n===3 May===\n[[President of Tanzania|Tanzanian President]] [[John Magufuli]] has criticized the quality of imported test kits, stating that the tests had returned positive on samples taken from a goat, sheep, and a [[Paw Paw|pawpaw]].<ref>{{Cite web|title=Tanzania president questions coronavirus kits after animal test|url=https://www.aljazeera.com/news/2020/05/tanzania-president-questions-coronavirus-kits-animal-test-200503174100809.html|website=www.aljazeera.com|access-date=2020-05-04}}</ref>\n\n===4 May===\nIn South Africa, Dondo Mogajane, the Director-General of the [[National Treasury (South Africa)|National Treasury]], has warned that South African economy could contract by 12% and that one-third of the workforce could be affected by the coronavirus as a result of the economic fallout of the COVID-19 pandemic.<ref name=\"Al Jazeera 4 May reports\">{{cite news |last1=Mayberry |first1=Kate |last2=Najjah |first2=Farah |title=Countries begin easing coronavirus lockdowns: Live updates |url=https://www.aljazeera.com/news/2020/05/confirmed-coronavirus-cases-exceed-35m-worldwide-live-updates-200503234441560.html |accessdate=4 May 2020 |work=[[Al Jazeera]] |date=4 May 2020}}</ref>\n\n== Reactions and measures in the Americas ==\n=== 1 May ===\n[[President of the United States|United States President]] [[Donald Trump]] has stated that he believes that the United States can never declare \"total victory\" over the coronavirus because too many people (about 63,000) have died. He added that he would regard the virus' elimination and the reopening of the US economy as a victory.<ref name=\"Al Jazeera 1 May reports\" />\n\nThe Director of the [[National Institute of Allergy and Infectious Diseases]] Dr [[Anthony Fauci]] has expressed optimism about [[Gilead Sciences]]' test vaccine [[remdesivir]] after initial tests indicated that it shortened the recovery time by an average of four days among test patients.  Later, the [[White House]] announced that Dr Fauci will not be allowed to testify at a [[United States Congress|Congressional]] inquiry into the [[Trump Administration]]'s handling of the coronavirus pandemic.<ref name=\"Al Jazeera 1 May reports\" />\n\n[[Governor of New York]] [[Andrew Cuomo]] has announced that all schools and colleges in New York state will remain close for the duration of the 2019&ndash;20 academic year.<ref name=\"Al Jazeera 1 May reports\" />\n\nTexas and Ohio have embarked with a gradual relaxation of lockdown restrictions on Friday. Georgia has allowed all businesses to reopen.<ref name=\"Al Jazeera 1 May reports\" />\n\nSeveral US airlines including [[Southwest Airlines]], [[Alaska Airlines]], [[United Airlines]], [[Delta Airlines]], the [[American Airlines Group]], and [[Frontier Airlines]] announce that all passengers will be required to wear face masks. Southwest Airlines has announced it will provide masks if patients forget to bring them.<ref name=\"Al Jazeera 1 May reports\" />\n\nThe stay-at-home orders in [[Marion County, Indiana]], [[Davis County, Utah]], and [[Summit County, Utah]] are scheduled to end.{{Citation needed|reason=|date=April 2020}}\n\n=== 2 May ===\nIn Brazil, prisoners at [[Paraquequara Penitentiary]] in [[Manaus]] took seven guards hostage to allegedly protest the suspension of family visits, poor living conditions, sweltering heat and lack of electricity.<ref name=\"Al Jazeera 2 May reports\">{{cite news |last1=Qazi |first1=Shereena |last2=Varshalomidze |first2= Tamila |title=Official says US missed chances to slow coronavirus: Live updates |url=https://www.aljazeera.com/news/2020/05/official-missed-chances-slow-coronavirus-live-updates-200501234526091.html |accessdate=2 May 2020 |work=[[Al Jazeera]] |date=2 May 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200503031937/https://www.aljazeera.com/news/2020/05/official-missed-chances-slow-coronavirus-live-updates-200501234526091.html|archive-date=3 May 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"Al Jazeera 3 May reports\">{{cite news|last1=Rashid|first1=Zaheena|date=3 May 2020|title=China reports two new coronavirus cases: Live updates|work=[[Al Jazeera]]|url=https://www.aljazeera.com/news/2020/05/riots-brazil-venezuela-prisons-coronavirus-live-updates-200502232536530.html|accessdate=3 May 2020|archive-url=http://web.archive.org/web/20200503222405/https://www.aljazeera.com/news/2020/05/riots-brazil-venezuela-prisons-coronavirus-live-updates-200502232536530.html|archive-date=3 May 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe United States [[Food and Drug Administration]] has authorized the use of [[Gilead Sciences]]'s antiviral drug [[remdesivir]] for emergency use in hospitals. The company's CEO Daniel O'Day announced that the company was donating 1.5 million vials of the drug to help patients.<ref name=\"Al Jazeera 3 May reports\" />\n\nThe [[National Aeronautic and Space Administration]] (NASA) and [[SpaceX]] have advised spectators to stay at home during the launch of two astronauts aboard a SpaceX rocket to the [[International Space Station]] on 27 May. This will be the first launch of astronauts from the [[Kennedy Space Center]] in Florida since 2011 and the first attempt by a private company to fly astronauts into space.<ref name=\"Al Jazeera 3 May reports\" />\n\nNew York Governor [[Andrew Cuomo]] has rebuffed calls to reopen New York state's economy, calling them premature. While acknowledging that people were struggling with their jobs, Cuomo stated that more understanding of the coronavirus was needed before reopening the state's economy.<ref name=\"Al Jazeera 3 May reports\" />\n\nThe [[International Monetary Fund]] has announced that it has approved a US$643 million economic relief loan for Ecuador in response to the coronavirus.<ref name=\"Al Jazeera 3 May reports\" />\n\n===3 May===\nBrazilian authorities have managed to restore order following an uprising at Puraquequara prison in [[Manaus]], where seven guards were taken hostage by prisoners protesting poor living conditions. Ten guards and five prisoners suffered non-critical injuries during the uprising.<ref name=\"Al Jazeera 3 May reports\" />\n\nUnited States President [[Donald Trump]] has expressed confidence that there will be a coronavirus vaccine by the end of the year during a media interview.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Higgins |first1=Tucker |title=Trump says he believes there will be a coronavirus vaccine \u2018by the end of the year\u2019 |url=https://www.cnbc.com/2020/05/03/trump-says-he-believes-there-will-be-a-coronavirus-vaccine-by-the-end-of-the-year.html |accessdate=4 May 2020 |work=[[CNBC]] |date=3 May 2020 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20200503234530/https://www.cnbc.com/2020/05/03/trump-says-he-believes-there-will-be-a-coronavirus-vaccine-by-the-end-of-the-year.html |archivedate=3 May 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Trump, at virtual Fox News town hall, predicts coronavirus vaccine by year's end |url=https://www.foxnews.com/us/trump-at-virtual-fox-news-town-hall-predicts-coronavirus-vaccine-by-years-end |accessdate=4 May 2020 |work=[[Fox News]] |date=4 May 2020 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20200504093523/https://www.foxnews.com/us/trump-at-virtual-fox-news-town-hall-predicts-coronavirus-vaccine-by-years-end |archivedate=4 May 2020}}</ref> He also expressed hope that schools and universities will reopen in September.<ref name=\"Al Jazeera 4 May reports\" />\n\nUnited States Secretary of State [[Mike Pompeo]] has claimed that there is \"enormous evidence\" that COVID-19 originated in a laboratory in Wuhan.<ref name=\"Al Jazeera 3 May reports\" />\n\n[[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]] [[Speaker of the House of Representatives (United States)|US Speaker of the House of Representatives]] [[Nancy Pelosi]] and [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]] [[Senate Majority Leader]] [[Mitch McConnell]] have declined an offer for quick COVID-19 tests from the [[Trump Administration]], stating that these resources are needed at the frontline.<ref name=\"Al Jazeera 3 May reports\" />\n\nNew York Governor [[Andrew Cuomo]] has thanked Qatar for sending critical supplies and aid to New York state.<ref name=\"Al Jazeera 3 May reports\" />\n\nIn Oregon, hundreds have staged protests in the state capital [[Salem, Oregon|Salem]] protesting against lockdown measures.<ref name=\"Al Jazeera 3 May reports\" />\n\nSwiss multinational health company [[Hoffman-La Roche]] has received approval from the US [[Food and Drug Administration]] to conduct its antibody test Elecsys Anti-SARS-CoV-2 on people. This antibody test will test whether people have been infected with the coronavirus and assess their immune system's response to the coronavirus.<ref name=\"Al Jazeera 2 May reports\" />\n\n=== 4 May ===\nThe stay-at-home orders in [[Minnesota]] and [[New Hampshire]] are scheduled to end.{{Citation needed|reason=|date=April 2020}}\n\n=== 8 May ===\nThe stay-at-home order in [[North Carolina]] is scheduled to end.{{Citation needed|reason=|date=April 2020}}\n\n=== 15 May ===\nThe stay-at-home orders in [[California]], [[Michigan]], [[Vermont]], [[Nevada]], [[New York (state)|New York]] and [[Washington, D.C.]] are scheduled to end.{{Citation needed|reason=|date=April 2020}}\n\n=== 23 May ===\nThe stay-at-home order in [[Washington (state)|Washington State]] is scheduled to end.{{Citation needed|reason=|date=April 2020}}\n\n=== 31 May ===\nThe stay-at-home orders in [[Illinois]], [[Alameda County, California]], [[Contra Costa County, California]], [[Marin County, California]], [[San Mateo County, California]], [[Santa Clara County, California]], [[Berkeley, California]], and [[San Francisco, California]] are scheduled to end.{{Citation needed|reason=|date=April 2020}}\n\n== Reactions and measures in Eastern Mediterranean ==\n===1 May===\nThe [[Special Inspector General for Afghanistan Reconstruction]] (SIGAR) has warned the [[United States Congress]] that Afghanistan is facing a health crisis as a result of the coronavirus pandemic due to its weak healthcare system, widespread malnutrition, porous borders, massive internal displacement, contiguity with Iran, and the ongoing [[War in Afghanistan (2001\u2013present)|conflict]].<ref name=\"Al Jazeera 1 May reports\" />\n\n[[Asad Qaiser]], the [[Speaker of the National Assembly of Pakistan]], tests positive for the coronavirus.<ref name=\"Al Jazeera 1 May reports\" />\n\n===2 May===\nSaudi Arabia's [[Ministry of Finance (Saudi Arabia)|Finance Minister]] [[Mohammed Al-Jadaan]] has announced that the Saudi Government will take \"strict and painful measures\" to deal with the economic impact of the coronavirus pandemic without giving any details.<ref name=\"Al Jazeera 2 May reports\" />\n\n===3 May===\n[[President of Iran|Iranian President]] [[Hassan Rouhani]] has announced that mosques in 312 Iranian counties will reopen but would have to comply with social distancing rules.<ref name=\"Al Jazeera 3 May reports\" />\n\nThe Jordanian Government has lifted all restrictions on economic activity including social distancing and health measures in order to jump-start the country's economy.<ref name=\"Al Jazeera 3 May reports\" />\n\nThe Palestinian stock exchange has resumed trading after 40 days of inactivity as part of the Palestinian Authority's efforts to relax lockdown restrictions. Chief Executive Ahmad Aweidah has announced that investors will be allowed to trade remotely in line with health regulations.<ref name=\"Al Jazeera 3 May reports\" />\n\nIn the United Arab Emirates, three shopping centres in [[Abu Dhabi]] have reopened after adopting safety measures including social distancing and installing thermal inspection devices.<ref name=\"Al Jazeera 3 May reports\" />\n\nIn Yemen, the [[Houthi]] Health Minister Taha Al-Mutawakel has appealed for the United Nations to send them more test kits due to the country's acute economic situation resulting from the [[Yemeni Civil War (2015\u2013present)|Yemeni Civil War]] and sanctions.<ref name=\"Al Jazeera 3 May reports\" />\n\n== Reactions and measures in Europe ==\n===1 May===\nAzerbaijan extends lockdown measures until 31 May.<ref name=\"Al Jazeera 1 May reports\" />\n\n[[President of France|French President]] [[Emmanuel Macron]] has announced that the end of the national lockdown on 11 May will mark the first step towards rebuilding the country's economy.<ref name=\"Al Jazeera 1 May reports\" />\n\nIn Germany, [[May Day]] protesters have defied a ban on social gatherings of more than 20 people by staging demonstrations in Berlin denouncing capitalism and calling for solidarity with refugees. Many protesters wore masks and stood at 1.5 meters apart.<ref name=\"Al Jazeera 1 May reports\" />\n\n[[Prime Minister of Hungary|Hungarian Prime Minister]] [[Viktor Orb\u00e1n]] has warned that Hungary needs to prepare for potential second wave of the coronavirus between October and November during the autumn season. In addition, organisers for the [[2020 Formula One World Championship]] in Hungary  announced that the race will take place on 2 August but without spectators to comply with Hungarian social distancing rules.<ref name=\"Al Jazeera 1 May reports\" />\n\nIrish [[Taoiseach]] [[Leo Varadkar]] has announced that people over the age of 70 will be able to leave their homes to go for a walk and drive from Tuesday onwards (5 May) and extended the travel limit for exercise from 2&nbsp;km to 5&nbsp;km. Varadkar also announced that the Irish economy would open in five stages between 18 May and 10 August.<ref name=\"Al Jazeera 1 May reports\" />\n\nIrish budget airliner [[Ryanair]] has announced that it plans to slash 3,000 pilot and cabin crew jobs as a result of the economic fallout of the coronavirus pandemic.<ref name=\"Al Jazeera 1 May reports\" />\n\n[[Prime Minister of Italy|Italian Prime Minister]] [[Giuseppe Conte]] has apologised for the Italian Government's delay in paying more than \u20ac$50 billion to assist struggling businesses and families.<ref name=\"Al Jazeera 1 May reports\" />\n\nIn [[Kazakhstan]], [[Air Astana]], [[SCAT Airlines|SCAT]], and [[Qazaq Air]] have resumed flight operations but middle seats will be empty to ensure social distancing. Passengers will also be required to undergo temperature checks and present certificates confirming that they have tested negative for the coronavirus.<ref name=\"Al Jazeera 1 May reports\" />\n\n[[Prime Minister of Slovakia]] [[Igor Matovic]] has lifted a quarantine placed on three [[Romani]] villages in April, which had been identified as clusters for the coronavirus.<ref name=\"Al Jazeera 1 May reports\" />\n\nSpanish [[Ministry of Economy and Business|Economy and Business Minister]] [[Nadia Calvi\u00f1o]] has forecast that Spain's gross domestic product will contract by 9.2 percent in 2020.<ref name=\"Al Jazeera 1 May reports\" />\n\nThe Swiss Government is testing a contact tracing app on 100 [[Swiss Army]] soldiers prior to its planned launch on 11 May.<ref name=\"Al Jazeera 1 May reports\" />\n\nThe Turkish Government has evacuated 300 of its citizens from Baghdad and Iraq's southern provinces through a land route with the support of Turkish government departments and the Turkish Embassy in Baghdad.<ref name=\"Al Jazeera 1 May reports\" />\n\nIn the United Kingdom, [[Heathrow Airport]] has reported a 12.7% drop in revenue to \u20a4593 million (US$754 million) in the first quarter of 2020. Passenger numbers also declined by 97% as a result of the coronavirus pandemic. A report by the Institute of Fiscal Studies found that patients from the [[British Bangladeshi|Bangladeshi]], [[British Pakistani|Pakistani]], and [[Black British people|Black]] ethnic communities had a higher mortality rate from the coronavirus than White Britons, reporting 2, 2.9, and 3.7 times the rate of white patients respectively. [[Secretary of State for Health|Health Secretary]] [[Matt Hancock]] announced that UK health authorities have conducted 122,347 tests, meeting the British Government's goal of testing 100,000 people.<ref name=\"Al Jazeera 1 May reports\" />\n\nThe [[World Health Organization]]'s (WHO) Director-General [[Tedros Adhanom]] has expressed \"grace concerns\" about the impact of the coronavirus on countries with \"weaker health systems.\" The WHO emergencies chief [[Michael J. Ryan (doctor)|Michael Ryan]] has stated that the coronavirus was of \"natural origin\", disputing US President [[Donald Trump]]'s allegation that it had originated in a Chinese laboratory.<ref name=\"Al Jazeera 1 May reports\" />\n\n===2 May===\nFrench [[Minister of Health (France)|Health Minister]] [[Olivier V\u00e9ran]] has announced that the French Government will extend the country's health emergency by two months in order to combat the coronavirus.<ref name=\"Al Jazeera 2 May reports\" />\n\nThe Spanish Government has eased lockdown measures by allowing all Spaniards to for walks or play sports after 48 days of home confinement. [[Prime Minister of Spain|Spanish Prime Minister]] [[Pedro Sanchez]] has announced that the government will make it compulsory to wear masks on public transportation. Madrid authorities have announced that they will distribute six million masks across the country from 4 May and another seven million to local authorities.<ref name=\"Al Jazeera 2 May reports\" />\n\nThe [[Ministry of Trade (Turkey)|Turkish Ministry of Trade]] has lifted export limits on medical equipment and a requirement for public companies to obtain advance permission to export medical supplies and equipment overseas. Turkey has dispatched medical supplies including ventilators to Somalia and the United States.<ref name=\"Al Jazeera 2 May reports\" />\n\n===3 May===\n[[Deputy Prime Minister of Armenia|Armenian Deputy Prime Minister]] [[Tigran Avinyan]] has allowed shops, restaurants, and bars to resume as part of the relaxation of its lockdown policies in order to ease the economic fallout of the coronavirus pandemic.<ref name=\"Al Jazeera 3 May reports\" />\n\nIn Austria, [[Vienna Airport]] announced that it will offer onsite coronavirus testing from Monday in order to minimise the risk of inbound passengers being quarantined. The test will cost \u20ac190 (US$209) and would be available in two to three hours.<ref name=\"Al Jazeera 3 May reports\" />\n\nHungarian budget airline [[Wizz Air]] has announced that it will resume flights from European cities to [[Abu Dhabi]] from June 2020.<ref name=\"Al Jazeera 3 May reports\" />\n\nIsrael has allowed first, second, and third grade students as well as students in the last two grades of high school to return to classes, which had been shut down in mid-March in order to contain the spread of the coronavirus.<ref name=\"Al Jazeera 3 May reports\" />\n\nUnited Kingdom Prime Minister [[Boris Johnson]] has acknowledged during a media interview that the British Government had made contingency plans in the event of his death from the coronavirus. [[Minister for the Cabinet Office]] [[Michael Gove]] announced that the British Government will also test a new coronavirus tracing programme in the [[Isle of Wight]].<ref name=\"Al Jazeera 3 May reports\" />\n\n===4 April===\nThe [[European Commission]] has approved \u20ac7 billion in French state aid to help beleaguered national carrier [[Air France]] cushion the economic fallout of the coronavirus pandemic.<ref name=\"Al Jazeera 4 May reports\" />\n\nThe [[Federal Ministry of Health (Germany)|Germany Health Minister]] [[Jen Spahn]] was warned that it could take years to develop a vaccine for COVID-19 in response to remarks by President Trump that they could have a vaccine by late 2020.<ref name=\"Al Jazeera 4 May reports\" />\n\n== Reactions and measures in South and Southeast Asia ==\n===1 May===\nThe Indian Government announces plans to make the contract tracing app [[Aarogya Setu]] compulsory for everything including going to work and traveling on public transportation, raising concerns about privacy and surveillance from digital experts. The Indian Government also announced that they would extend the nationwide lockdown for two weeks after 4 May but would ease restrictions in lower risk areas. Travel restrictions on air, rail, metro, and inter-state movement by road remain suspended while schools, colleges, hotels, restaurants, shopping malls, cinemas, and places of worship remain closed.<ref name=\"Al Jazeera 1 May reports\" />\n\nIndian authorities have also organised a special train transporting 1,200 migrant workers, who had been stranded as a result of lockdown measures, from [[Lingampally]]{{disambiguation needed|date=May 2020}} in southern state of [[Telangana]] to [[Hatia]] in  the eastern state of [[Jharkhand]]. During a video conference, several film producers, directors and actors opined that it would take two years for [[Bollywood]] to recover.<ref name=\"Al Jazeera 1 May reports\" />\n\n[[Prime Minister of Malaysia|Malaysian Prime Minister]] [[Muhyiddin Yassin]] announced that most businesses will be allowed to reopen from 4 May with the exception of cinemas and bazaars since they involve large gatherings.<ref name=\"Al Jazeera 1 May reports\" /> Malaysian [[Minister of Transport (Malaysia)|Transport Minister]] Dr [[Wee Ka Siong]] confirmed that all public transportation services would resume on 4 May as part of the gradual relaxation of the country's [[2020 Malaysia movement control order|movement control order]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Public transport services to resume operations on May 4 |url=https://www.thesundaily.my/home/public-transport-services-to-resume-operations-on-may-4-MD2360248#pk_campaign=MASwpn&pk_kwd=Public+transport+services+to+resume+operations+on+May+4 |accessdate=1 May 2020 |work=[[The Sun (Malaysia)|The Sun]] |date=1 May 2020 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20200501223843/https://www.thesundaily.my/home/public-transport-services-to-resume-operations-on-may-4-MD2360248 |archivedate=1 May 2020}}</ref> [[Human Rights Watch]] and the [[Asia Pacific Refugee Rights Network]] have reported that over 700 foreign migrant workers and refugees including [[Rohingya]] have been detained by Malaysian law enforcement authorities during the coronavirus pandemic.<ref>{{cite news |title=Malaysia 'detains migrants, refugees' amid coronavirus lockdown |url=https://www.aljazeera.com/news/2020/05/malaysia-detains-migrants-refugees-coronavirus-lockdown-200501134602431.html |accessdate=2 May 2020 |work=[[Al Jazeera]] |date=1 May 2020 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20200502020549/https://www.aljazeera.com/news/2020/05/malaysia-detains-migrants-refugees-coronavirus-lockdown-200501134602431.html |archivedate=2 May 2020}}</ref>\n\n===2 May===\nThe Indian Government has extended the country's coronavirus lockdown by two weeks.<ref name=\"Al Jazeera 2 May reports\" />\n\nThe [[United Nations]] in Malaysia's Head of Communications and Advocacy, Ahmad Hafiz Osman, called for migrants, refugees, asylum seekers, and stateless individuals in Malaysia to have access to health services and services without fear of repercussions.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Nur |first1=Alisha |title=UN Malaysia voices concern over large-scale arrests of undocumented migrants in KL |url=https://www.thesundaily.my/local/un-malaysia-voices-concern-over-large-scale-arrests-of-undocumented-migrants-in-kl-FE2363205#pk_campaign=MASwpn&pk_kwd=UN+Malaysia+voices+concern+over+large-scale+arrests+of+undocumented+migrants+in+KL |accessdate=2 May 2020 |work=[[The Sun (Malaysia)|The Sun]] |date=2 May 2020 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20200502093020/https://www.thesundaily.my/local/un-malaysia-voices-concern-over-large-scale-arrests-of-undocumented-migrants-in-kl-FE2363205 |archivedate=2 May 2020}}</ref>\n\n[[Minister for Health (Singapore)|Health Minister]] [[Gan Kim Yong]] has announced that Singapore will lessen restrictions including allowing some businesses to resume operations on 12 May and that some students will be allowed to return to school from 19 May.<ref name=\"Al Jazeera 2 May reports\" />\n\n===4 May===\nThe Indian Government has indicated that it will ease lockdown restrictions although the nationwide lockdown will remain in force until 17 May. The Indian government has also colour-coded states and cities into red, orange, and green zones based on the number of cases. In red areas, businesses can operate at one-third capacity, construction can resume provided workers have onsite accommodation, and standalone shops can reopen. In orange zones, taxis are allowed to operate. In green zones, businesses can resume all activities unless they are prohibited under the national lockdown. At the national level, all travel remains suspended while all schools, shopping malls, hotels, and public spaces remain closed.<ref name=\"Al Jazeera 4 May reports\" />\n\nThe Malaysian federal government has allowed businesses including restaurants to reopen but they must adhere to social distancing, hygiene, and contact tracing requirements. Due to a spike of cases over the weekends, some state governments have indicated that they will not ease restrictions.<ref name=\"Al Jazeera 4 May reports\" />\n\n== Reactions and measures in Western Pacific ==\n===1 May===\n[[Prime Minister of Australia|Australian Prime Minister]] [[Scott Morrison]] has announced that the Australian Government will make a decision by next Friday (8 May) on whether to relax lockdown movement restrictions. Morrison also described Australia's [[Australia\u2013China relations|relations]] with China as mutually beneficial in the face of tensions over Canberra seeking an international inquiry into China's handling of the COVID-19 pandemic in [[Wuhan]]. Later, Morrison stated at a press conference that he had no evidence to suggest that the coronavirus originated in a Wuhan laboratory.<ref name=\"Al Jazeera 1 May reports\" />\n\nChinese authorities announced that they will be reopening Beijing's Palace Museum on 1 May. [[Hubei]] provincial authorities have announced that the province will lower its emergency response level from highest to second highest on 2 April.<ref name=\"Al Jazeera 1 May reports\" />\n\n[[Prime Minister of Japan|Japanese Prime Minister]] [[Shinzo Abe]] announced that the Japanese Government would decide by Monday (4 May) whether to extend the country's state of emergency, which is set to expire on 6 May.<ref name=\"Al Jazeera 1 May reports\" />\n\nThe Philippines Government has relaxed coronavirus restrictions by placing areas with fewer cases under a more relaxed quarantine; allowing work, public transport and businesses to resume operations at a reduced capacity.<ref name=\"Al Jazeera 1 May reports\" />\n\nAccording to figures released by the South Korean [[Ministry of Trade, Industry and Energy (South Korea)|Ministry of Trade, Industry and Energy]], South Korean exports declined by 24.3 percent in April 2020.<ref name=\"Al Jazeera 1 May reports\" />\n\n[[World Health Organization]] spokesperson [[Tarik Jasarevic]] has stated that the international organisation is seeking an invitation from China to participate in investigations into the animal origins of the coronavirus.<ref name=\"Al Jazeera 1 May reports\" />\n\n===2 May===\nThe [[Japan Sumo Association]] has announced that it will reconsider rescheduling its grand summer tournament scheduled for 24 May if the Japanese Government decides to extend the nationwide lockdown, which is scheduled to end on 6 May.<ref name=\"Al Jazeera 2 May reports\" />\n<ref name=\"Al Jazeera 2 May reports\" />\n\nIn the Philippines, Associate Justice of the [[Supreme Court of the Philippines|Supreme Court]] [[Marvic Leonen]] has confirmed that the Philippines Government has released 9,731 prisoners, mainly those awaiting trial who could not afford bail, in an effort to ease the spread of the coronavirus in the country's overcrowded prison system.<ref name=\"Al Jazeera 2 May reports\" />\n\n===3 May===\nThe Philippines has banned incoming flights for one week to curb the spread of the coronavirus. 20,000 repatriated Filipinos are undergoing mandatory quarantine.<ref name=\"Al Jazeera 3 May reports\" />\n\nThailand has eased restrictions on restaurants, hair salons and outdoor markets as long as they adhere to social distancing rules and conduct temperature tests.<ref name=\"Al Jazeera 3 May reports\" />\n\n[[Prime Minister of South Korea|South Korean Prime Minister]] [[Chung Sye-Kyun]] has announced that the country will ease social distancing restrictions, allowing businesses to reopen and allow public gatherings to take place provided they follow disinfection guidelines.<ref name=\"Al Jazeera 3 May reports\" />\n\n===4 May===\nIn Australia, the state New South Wales has begun opening schools on a staggered basis as part of a process of easing lockdown restrictions. [[Premier of New South Wales|New South Wales Premier]] [[Gladys Berejiklian]] confirmed that a seven year old boy had tested positive for the coronavirus, prompting the closure of his school. Meanwhile, Victoria state has asked parents to keep their children at home until the middle of the year.<ref name=\"Al Jazeera 4 May reports\" />\n\nThe [[Associated Press]] has reported that United States intelligence officials believed that China covered up the extent of the coronavirus outbreak in order to stock up on medical supplies needed to respond to it, citing a four-page [[United States Department of Homeland Security|Department of Homeland Security]] report dating back to 1 May.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Weisert |first1=Will |title=DHS report: China hid virus\u2019 severity to hoard supplies |url=https://apnews.com/bf685dcf52125be54e030834ab7062a8 |accessdate=4 May 2020 |agency=[[Associated Press]] |date=4 May 2020}}</ref>\n\nJapanese Economy Minister [[Yasutoshi Nishimura]] has announced that the Japanese Government is seeking to extend the country's nationwide state of emergency until 31 May. The government's state of emergency is due to expire on 6 May (Wednesday).<ref name=\"Al Jazeera 4 May reports\" />\n\n[[Prime Minister of New Zealand|New Zealand Prime Minister]] [[Jacinda Ardern]] has accepted an invitation from Australian Prime Minister Scott Morrison to participate in a meeting of Australia's emergency cabinet on Tuesday via video conference. Topics including the possible creation of an Australian-New Zealand travel bubble.<ref name=\"Al Jazeera 4 May reports\" />\n\nThe South Korean [[Ministry of Education (South Korea)|Education Minister]] [[Yoo Eun-hae]] has announced that the South Korean Government will reopen schools in stages from 13 May. She also indicated that schools may switch to online learning if a student contracts COVID-19.<ref name=\"Al Jazeera 4 May reports\" />\n\n[[FINA]] (the International Swimming Federation) has postponed the [[2021 World Aquatics Championships]], scheduled to be held in [[Fukuoka]], Japan in May 2021 to 13\u201329 May 2022.<ref name=\"Al Jazeera 4 May reports\" />\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Responses to the COVID-19 pandemic in February 2020]]\n* [[Responses to the COVID-19 pandemic in March 2020]]\n* [[Responses to the COVID-19 pandemic in April 2020]]\n* [[Timeline of the COVID-19 pandemic from November to December 2019]]\n* [[Timeline of the COVID-19 pandemic in January 2020]]\n* [[Timeline of the COVID-19 pandemic in February 2020]]\n* [[Timeline of the COVID-19 pandemic in March 2020]]\n* [[Timeline of the COVID-19 pandemic in April 2020]]\n* [[Timeline of the COVID-19 pandemic in May 2020]]\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|timeline}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Responses to the 2019-20 coronavirus pandemic in May 2020}}\n[[Category:May 2020 events]]\n[[Category:Timeline of the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|*2020-05]]\n[[Category:Responses to the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|*2020-05]]\n[[Category:Timelines of current events|coronavirus pandemic]]\n", "text_old": "{{See also|COVID-19 pandemic|Timeline of the COVID-19 pandemic in May 2020}}\n{{short description|Sequence of major events in a virus pandemic}}\n{{Main|Timeline of the COVID-19 pandemic}}\n{{EngvarB|date=April 2020}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Expand list|date=April 2020}}\n{{COVID-19 pandemic sidebar |expanded=timeline}}\n\nThis article documents the chronology of the response to the [[COVID-19 pandemic]] in May 2020, which originated in [[Wuhan]], China in December 2019. Some developments may become known or fully understood only in retrospect. Reporting on this pandemic began in [[Timeline of the COVID-19 pandemic from November to December 2019|December 2019]].\n{{TOC limit}}\n\n== Reactions and measures in Africa ==\n===1 May===\nSouth Africa has begun to loosen its lockdown restrictions, allowing some businesses including winter clothing, textile, and packaging factories to resume operations. Restaurants will be allowed to provide takeaway services. Recreational activities such as walking, cycling, and running will be allowed for three hours a day. The South African Government has maintained a ban on the sales of cigarettes and alcohol.<ref name=\"Al Jazeera 1 May reports\">{{cite news |last1=Regencia |first1=Ted |last2=Aziz |first2=Saba |last3=Stepansky |first3=Joseph |title=WHO says coronavirus 'natural in origin': Live updates |url=https://www.aljazeera.com/news/2020/04/trump-suggests-coronavirus-linked-wuhan-lab-live-updates-200430231206079.html |accessdate=1 May 2020 |work=[[Al Jazeera]] |date=1 May 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200501224421/https://www.aljazeera.com/news/2020/04/trump-suggests-coronavirus-linked-wuhan-lab-live-updates-200430231206079.html|archive-date=1 May 2020}}</ref>\n\n[[President of Zimbabwe]] [[Emmerson Mnangagwa]] has extended Zimbabwe's lockdown for two more weeks and announced a US$720 million stimulus for affected companies.<ref name=\"Al Jazeera 1 May reports\" />\n\n===3 May===\n[[President of Tanzania|Tanzanian President]] [[John Magufuli]] has criticized the quality of imported test kits, stating that the tests had returned positive on samples taken from a goat, sheep, and a [[Paw Paw|pawpaw]].<ref>{{Cite web|title=Tanzania president questions coronavirus kits after animal test|url=https://www.aljazeera.com/news/2020/05/tanzania-president-questions-coronavirus-kits-animal-test-200503174100809.html|website=www.aljazeera.com|access-date=2020-05-04}}</ref>\n\n===4 May===\nIn South Africa, Dondo Mogajane, the Director-General of the [[National Treasury (South Africa)|National Treasury]], has warned that South African economy could contract by 12% and that one-third of the workforce could be affected by the coronavirus as a result of the economic fallout of the COVID-19 pandemic.<ref name=\"Al Jazeera 4 May reports\">{{cite news |last1=Mayberry |first1=Kate |last2=Najjah |first2=Farah |title=Countries begin easing coronavirus lockdowns: Live updates |url=https://www.aljazeera.com/news/2020/05/confirmed-coronavirus-cases-exceed-35m-worldwide-live-updates-200503234441560.html |accessdate=4 May 2020 |work=[[Al Jazeera]] |date=4 May 2020}}</ref>\n\n== Reactions and measures in the Americas ==\n=== 1 May ===\n[[President of the United States|United States President]] [[Donald Trump]] has stated that he believes that the United States can never declare \"total victory\" over the coronavirus because too many people (about 63,000) have died. He added that he would regard the virus' elimination and the reopening of the US economy as a victory.<ref name=\"Al Jazeera 1 May reports\" />\n\nThe Director of the [[National Institute of Allergy and Infectious Diseases]] Dr [[Anthony Fauci]] has expressed optimism about [[Gilead Sciences]]' test vaccine [[remdesivir]] after initial tests indicated that it shortened the recovery time by an average of four days among test patients.  Later, the [[White House]] announced that Dr Fauci will not be allowed to testify at a [[United States Congress|Congressional]] inquiry into the [[Trump Administration]]'s handling of the coronavirus pandemic.<ref name=\"Al Jazeera 1 May reports\" />\n\n[[Governor of New York]] [[Andrew Cuomo]] has announced that all schools and colleges in New York state will remain close for the duration of the 2019&ndash;20 academic year.<ref name=\"Al Jazeera 1 May reports\" />\n\nTexas and Ohio have embarked with a gradual relaxation of lockdown restrictions on Friday. Georgia has allowed all businesses to reopen.<ref name=\"Al Jazeera 1 May reports\" />\n\nSeveral US airlines including [[Southwest Airlines]], [[Alaska Airlines]], [[United Airlines]], [[Delta Airlines]], the [[American Airlines Group]], and [[Frontier Airlines]] announce that all passengers will be required to wear face masks. Southwest Airlines has announced it will provide masks if patients forget to bring them.<ref name=\"Al Jazeera 1 May reports\" />\n\nThe stay-at-home orders in [[Marion County, Indiana]], [[Davis County, Utah]], and [[Summit County, Utah]] are scheduled to end.{{Citation needed|reason=|date=April 2020}}\n\n=== 2 May ===\nIn Brazil, prisoners at [[Paraquequara Penitentiary]] in [[Manaus]] took seven guards hostage to allegedly protest the suspension of family visits, poor living conditions, sweltering heat and lack of electricity.<ref name=\"Al Jazeera 2 May reports\">{{cite news |last1=Qazi |first1=Shereena |last2=Varshalomidze |first2= Tamila |title=Official says US missed chances to slow coronavirus: Live updates |url=https://www.aljazeera.com/news/2020/05/official-missed-chances-slow-coronavirus-live-updates-200501234526091.html |accessdate=2 May 2020 |work=[[Al Jazeera]] |date=2 May 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200503031937/https://www.aljazeera.com/news/2020/05/official-missed-chances-slow-coronavirus-live-updates-200501234526091.html|archive-date=3 May 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"Al Jazeera 3 May reports\">{{cite news|last1=Rashid|first1=Zaheena|date=3 May 2020|title=China reports two new coronavirus cases: Live updates|work=[[Al Jazeera]]|url=https://www.aljazeera.com/news/2020/05/riots-brazil-venezuela-prisons-coronavirus-live-updates-200502232536530.html|accessdate=3 May 2020|archive-url=http://web.archive.org/web/20200503222405/https://www.aljazeera.com/news/2020/05/riots-brazil-venezuela-prisons-coronavirus-live-updates-200502232536530.html|archive-date=3 May 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe United States [[Food and Drug Administration]] has authorized the use of [[Gilead Sciences]]'s antiviral drug [[remdesivir]] for emergency use in hospitals. The company's CEO Daniel O'Day announced that the company was donating 1.5 million vials of the drug to help patients.<ref name=\"Al Jazeera 3 May reports\" />\n\nThe [[National Aeronautic and Space Administration]] (NASA) and [[SpaceX]] have advised spectators to stay at home during the launch of two astronauts aboard a SpaceX rocket to the [[International Space Station]] on 27 May. This will be the first launch of astronauts from the [[Kennedy Space Center]] in Florida since 2011 and the first attempt by a private company to fly astronauts into space.<ref name=\"Al Jazeera 3 May reports\" />\n\nNew York Governor [[Andrew Cuomo]] has rebuffed calls to reopen New York state's economy, calling them premature. While acknowledging that people were struggling with their jobs, Cuomo stated that more understanding of the coronavirus was needed before reopening the state's economy.<ref name=\"Al Jazeera 3 May reports\" />\n\nThe [[International Monetary Fund]] has announced that it has approved a US$643 million economic relief loan for Ecuador in response to the coronavirus.<ref name=\"Al Jazeera 3 May reports\" />\n\n===3 May===\nBrazilian authorities have managed to restore order following an uprising at Puraquequara prison in [[Manaus]], where seven guards were taken hostage by prisoners protesting poor living conditions. Ten guards and five prisoners suffered non-critical injuries during the uprising.<ref name=\"Al Jazeera 3 May reports\" />\n\nUnited States President [[Donald Trump]] has expressed confidence that there will be a coronavirus vaccine by the end of the year during a media interview.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Higgins |first1=Tucker |title=Trump says he believes there will be a coronavirus vaccine \u2018by the end of the year\u2019 |url=https://www.cnbc.com/2020/05/03/trump-says-he-believes-there-will-be-a-coronavirus-vaccine-by-the-end-of-the-year.html |accessdate=4 May 2020 |work=[[CNBC]] |date=3 May 2020 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20200503234530/https://www.cnbc.com/2020/05/03/trump-says-he-believes-there-will-be-a-coronavirus-vaccine-by-the-end-of-the-year.html |archivedate=3 May 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Trump, at virtual Fox News town hall, predicts coronavirus vaccine by year's end |url=https://www.foxnews.com/us/trump-at-virtual-fox-news-town-hall-predicts-coronavirus-vaccine-by-years-end |accessdate=4 May 2020 |work=[[Fox News]] |date=4 May 2020 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20200504093523/https://www.foxnews.com/us/trump-at-virtual-fox-news-town-hall-predicts-coronavirus-vaccine-by-years-end |archivedate=4 May 2020}}</ref> He also expressed hope that schools and universities will reopen in September.<ref name=\"Al Jazeera 4 May reports\" />\n\nUnited States Secretary of State [[Mike Pompeo]] has claimed that there is \"enormous evidence\" that COVID-19 originated in a laboratory in Wuhan.<ref name=\"Al Jazeera 3 May reports\" />\n\n[[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]] [[Speaker of the House of Representatives (United States)|US Speaker of the House of Representatives]] [[Nancy Pelosi]] and [[Republican Party (United States)|Republic]] [[Senate Majority Leader]] [[Mitch McConnell]] have declined an offer for quick COVID-19 tests from the [[Trump Administration]], stating that these resources are needed at the frontline.<ref name=\"Al Jazeera 3 May reports\" />\n\nNew York Governor [[Andrew Cuomo]] has thanked Qatar for sending critical supplies and aid to New York state.<ref name=\"Al Jazeera 3 May reports\" />\n\nIn Oregon, hundreds have staged protests in the state capital [[Salem, Oregon|Salem]] protesting against lockdown measures.<ref name=\"Al Jazeera 3 May reports\" />\n\nSwiss multinational health company [[Hoffman-La Roche]] has received approval from the US [[Food and Drug Administration]] to conduct its antibody test Elecsys Anti-SARS-CoV-2 on people. This antibody test will test whether people have been infected with the coronavirus and assess their immune system's response to the coronavirus.<ref name=\"Al Jazeera 2 May reports\" />\n\n=== 4 May ===\nThe stay-at-home orders in [[Minnesota]] and [[New Hampshire]] are scheduled to end.{{Citation needed|reason=|date=April 2020}}\n\n=== 8 May ===\nThe stay-at-home order in [[North Carolina]] is scheduled to end.{{Citation needed|reason=|date=April 2020}}\n\n=== 15 May ===\nThe stay-at-home orders in [[California]], [[Michigan]], [[Vermont]], [[Nevada]], [[New York (state)|New York]] and [[Washington, D.C.]] are scheduled to end.{{Citation needed|reason=|date=April 2020}}\n\n=== 23 May ===\nThe stay-at-home order in [[Washington (state)|Washington State]] is scheduled to end.{{Citation needed|reason=|date=April 2020}}\n\n=== 31 May ===\nThe stay-at-home orders in [[Illinois]], [[Alameda County, California]], [[Contra Costa County, California]], [[Marin County, California]], [[San Mateo County, California]], [[Santa Clara County, California]], [[Berkeley, California]], and [[San Francisco, California]] are scheduled to end.{{Citation needed|reason=|date=April 2020}}\n\n== Reactions and measures in Eastern Mediterranean ==\n===1 May===\nThe [[Special Inspector General for Afghanistan Reconstruction]] (SIGAR) has warned the [[United States Congress]] that Afghanistan is facing a health crisis as a result of the coronavirus pandemic due to its weak healthcare system, widespread malnutrition, porous borders, massive internal displacement, contiguity with Iran, and the ongoing [[War in Afghanistan (2001\u2013present)|conflict]].<ref name=\"Al Jazeera 1 May reports\" />\n\n[[Asad Qaiser]], the [[Speaker of the National Assembly of Pakistan]], tests positive for the coronavirus.<ref name=\"Al Jazeera 1 May reports\" />\n\n===2 May===\nSaudi Arabia's [[Ministry of Finance (Saudi Arabia)|Finance Minister]] [[Mohammed Al-Jadaan]] has announced that the Saudi Government will take \"strict and painful measures\" to deal with the economic impact of the coronavirus pandemic without giving any details.<ref name=\"Al Jazeera 2 May reports\" />\n\n===3 May===\n[[President of Iran|Iranian President]] [[Hassan Rouhani]] has announced that mosques in 312 Iranian counties will reopen but would have to comply with social distancing rules.<ref name=\"Al Jazeera 3 May reports\" />\n\nThe Jordanian Government has lifted all restrictions on economic activity including social distancing and health measures in order to jump-start the country's economy.<ref name=\"Al Jazeera 3 May reports\" />\n\nThe Palestinian stock exchange has resumed trading after 40 days of inactivity as part of the Palestinian Authority's efforts to relax lockdown restrictions. Chief Executive Ahmad Aweidah has announced that investors will be allowed to trade remotely in line with health regulations.<ref name=\"Al Jazeera 3 May reports\" />\n\nIn the United Arab Emirates, three shopping centres in [[Abu Dhabi]] have reopened after adopting safety measures including social distancing and installing thermal inspection devices.<ref name=\"Al Jazeera 3 May reports\" />\n\nIn Yemen, the [[Houthi]] Health Minister Taha Al-Mutawakel has appealed for the United Nations to send them more test kits due to the country's acute economic situation resulting from the [[Yemeni Civil War (2015\u2013present)|Yemeni Civil War]] and sanctions.<ref name=\"Al Jazeera 3 May reports\" />\n\n== Reactions and measures in Europe ==\n===1 May===\nAzerbaijan extends lockdown measures until 31 May.<ref name=\"Al Jazeera 1 May reports\" />\n\n[[President of France|French President]] [[Emmanuel Macron]] has announced that the end of the national lockdown on 11 May will mark the first step towards rebuilding the country's economy.<ref name=\"Al Jazeera 1 May reports\" />\n\nIn Germany, [[May Day]] protesters have defied a ban on social gatherings of more than 20 people by staging demonstrations in Berlin denouncing capitalism and calling for solidarity with refugees. Many protesters wore masks and stood at 1.5 meters apart.<ref name=\"Al Jazeera 1 May reports\" />\n\n[[Prime Minister of Hungary|Hungarian Prime Minister]] [[Viktor Orb\u00e1n]] has warned that Hungary needs to prepare for potential second wave of the coronavirus between October and November during the autumn season. In addition, organisers for the [[2020 Formula One World Championship]] in Hungary  announced that the race will take place on 2 August but without spectators to comply with Hungarian social distancing rules.<ref name=\"Al Jazeera 1 May reports\" />\n\nIrish [[Taoiseach]] [[Leo Varadkar]] has announced that people over the age of 70 will be able to leave their homes to go for a walk and drive from Tuesday onwards (5 May) and extended the travel limit for exercise from 2&nbsp;km to 5&nbsp;km. Varadkar also announced that the Irish economy would open in five stages between 18 May and 10 August.<ref name=\"Al Jazeera 1 May reports\" />\n\nIrish budget airliner [[Ryanair]] has announced that it plans to slash 3,000 pilot and cabin crew jobs as a result of the economic fallout of the coronavirus pandemic.<ref name=\"Al Jazeera 1 May reports\" />\n\n[[Prime Minister of Italy|Italian Prime Minister]] [[Giuseppe Conte]] has apologised for the Italian Government's delay in paying more than \u20ac$50 billion to assist struggling businesses and families.<ref name=\"Al Jazeera 1 May reports\" />\n\nIn [[Kazakhstan]], [[Air Astana]], [[SCAT Airlines|SCAT]], and [[Qazaq Air]] have resumed flight operations but middle seats will be empty to ensure social distancing. Passengers will also be required to undergo temperature checks and present certificates confirming that they have tested negative for the coronavirus.<ref name=\"Al Jazeera 1 May reports\" />\n\n[[Prime Minister of Slovakia]] [[Igor Matovic]] has lifted a quarantine placed on three [[Romani]] villages in April, which had been identified as clusters for the coronavirus.<ref name=\"Al Jazeera 1 May reports\" />\n\nSpanish [[Ministry of Economy and Business|Economy and Business Minister]] [[Nadia Calvi\u00f1o]] has forecast that Spain's gross domestic product will contract by 9.2 percent in 2020.<ref name=\"Al Jazeera 1 May reports\" />\n\nThe Swiss Government is testing a contact tracing app on 100 [[Swiss Army]] soldiers prior to its planned launch on 11 May.<ref name=\"Al Jazeera 1 May reports\" />\n\nThe Turkish Government has evacuated 300 of its citizens from Baghdad and Iraq's southern provinces through a land route with the support of Turkish government departments and the Turkish Embassy in Baghdad.<ref name=\"Al Jazeera 1 May reports\" />\n\nIn the United Kingdom, [[Heathrow Airport]] has reported a 12.7% drop in revenue to \u20a4593 million (US$754 million) in the first quarter of 2020. Passenger numbers also declined by 97% as a result of the coronavirus pandemic. A report by the Institute of Fiscal Studies found that patients from the [[British Bangladeshi|Bangladeshi]], [[British Pakistani|Pakistani]], and [[Black British people|Black]] ethnic communities had a higher mortality rate from the coronavirus than White Britons, reporting 2, 2.9, and 3.7 times the rate of white patients respectively. [[Secretary of State for Health|Health Secretary]] [[Matt Hancock]] announced that UK health authorities have conducted 122,347 tests, meeting the British Government's goal of testing 100,000 people.<ref name=\"Al Jazeera 1 May reports\" />\n\nThe [[World Health Organization]]'s (WHO) Director-General [[Tedros Adhanom]] has expressed \"grace concerns\" about the impact of the coronavirus on countries with \"weaker health systems.\" The WHO emergencies chief [[Michael J. Ryan (doctor)|Michael Ryan]] has stated that the coronavirus was of \"natural origin\", disputing US President [[Donald Trump]]'s allegation that it had originated in a Chinese laboratory.<ref name=\"Al Jazeera 1 May reports\" />\n\n===2 May===\nFrench [[Minister of Health (France)|Health Minister]] [[Olivier V\u00e9ran]] has announced that the French Government will extend the country's health emergency by two months in order to combat the coronavirus.<ref name=\"Al Jazeera 2 May reports\" />\n\nThe Spanish Government has eased lockdown measures by allowing all Spaniards to for walks or play sports after 48 days of home confinement. [[Prime Minister of Spain|Spanish Prime Minister]] [[Pedro Sanchez]] has announced that the government will make it compulsory to wear masks on public transportation. Madrid authorities have announced that they will distribute six million masks across the country from 4 May and another seven million to local authorities.<ref name=\"Al Jazeera 2 May reports\" />\n\nThe [[Ministry of Trade (Turkey)|Turkish Ministry of Trade]] has lifted export limits on medical equipment and a requirement for public companies to obtain advance permission to export medical supplies and equipment overseas. Turkey has dispatched medical supplies including ventilators to Somalia and the United States.<ref name=\"Al Jazeera 2 May reports\" />\n\n===3 May===\n[[Deputy Prime Minister of Armenia|Armenian Deputy Prime Minister]] [[Tigran Avinyan]] has allowed shops, restaurants, and bars to resume as part of the relaxation of its lockdown policies in order to ease the economic fallout of the coronavirus pandemic.<ref name=\"Al Jazeera 3 May reports\" />\n\nIn Austria, [[Vienna Airport]] announced that it will offer onsite coronavirus testing from Monday in order to minimise the risk of inbound passengers being quarantined. The test will cost \u20ac190 (US$209) and would be available in two to three hours.<ref name=\"Al Jazeera 3 May reports\" />\n\nHungarian budget airline [[Wizz Air]] has announced that it will resume flights from European cities to [[Abu Dhabi]] from June 2020.<ref name=\"Al Jazeera 3 May reports\" />\n\nIsrael has allowed first, second, and third grade students as well as students in the last two grades of high school to return to classes, which had been shut down in mid-March in order to contain the spread of the coronavirus.<ref name=\"Al Jazeera 3 May reports\" />\n\nUnited Kingdom Prime Minister [[Boris Johnson]] has acknowledged during a media interview that the British Government had made contingency plans in the event of his death from the coronavirus. [[Minister for the Cabinet Office]] [[Michael Gove]] announced that the British Government will also test a new coronavirus tracing programme in the [[Isle of Wight]].<ref name=\"Al Jazeera 3 May reports\" />\n\n===4 April===\nThe [[European Commission]] has approved \u20ac7 billion in French state aid to help beleaguered national carrier [[Air France]] cushion the economic fallout of the coronavirus pandemic.<ref name=\"Al Jazeera 4 May reports\" />\n\nThe [[Federal Ministry of Health (Germany)|Germany Health Minister]] [[Jen Spahn]] was warned that it could take years to develop a vaccine for COVID-19 in response to remarks by President Trump that they could have a vaccine by late 2020.<ref name=\"Al Jazeera 4 May reports\" />\n\n== Reactions and measures in South and Southeast Asia ==\n===1 May===\nThe Indian Government announces plans to make the contract tracing app [[Aarogya Setu]] compulsory for everything including going to work and traveling on public transportation, raising concerns about privacy and surveillance from digital experts. The Indian Government also announced that they would extend the nationwide lockdown for two weeks after 4 May but would ease restrictions in lower risk areas. Travel restrictions on air, rail, metro, and inter-state movement by road remain suspended while schools, colleges, hotels, restaurants, shopping malls, cinemas, and places of worship remain closed.<ref name=\"Al Jazeera 1 May reports\" />\n\nIndian authorities have also organised a special train transporting 1,200 migrant workers, who had been stranded as a result of lockdown measures, from [[Lingampally]]{{disambiguation needed|date=May 2020}} in southern state of [[Telangana]] to [[Hatia]] in  the eastern state of [[Jharkhand]]. During a video conference, several film producers, directors and actors opined that it would take two years for [[Bollywood]] to recover.<ref name=\"Al Jazeera 1 May reports\" />\n\n[[Prime Minister of Malaysia|Malaysian Prime Minister]] [[Muhyiddin Yassin]] announced that most businesses will be allowed to reopen from 4 May with the exception of cinemas and bazaars since they involve large gatherings.<ref name=\"Al Jazeera 1 May reports\" /> Malaysian [[Minister of Transport (Malaysia)|Transport Minister]] Dr [[Wee Ka Siong]] confirmed that all public transportation services would resume on 4 May as part of the gradual relaxation of the country's [[2020 Malaysia movement control order|movement control order]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Public transport services to resume operations on May 4 |url=https://www.thesundaily.my/home/public-transport-services-to-resume-operations-on-may-4-MD2360248#pk_campaign=MASwpn&pk_kwd=Public+transport+services+to+resume+operations+on+May+4 |accessdate=1 May 2020 |work=[[The Sun (Malaysia)|The Sun]] |date=1 May 2020 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20200501223843/https://www.thesundaily.my/home/public-transport-services-to-resume-operations-on-may-4-MD2360248 |archivedate=1 May 2020}}</ref> [[Human Rights Watch]] and the [[Asia Pacific Refugee Rights Network]] have reported that over 700 foreign migrant workers and refugees including [[Rohingya]] have been detained by Malaysian law enforcement authorities during the coronavirus pandemic.<ref>{{cite news |title=Malaysia 'detains migrants, refugees' amid coronavirus lockdown |url=https://www.aljazeera.com/news/2020/05/malaysia-detains-migrants-refugees-coronavirus-lockdown-200501134602431.html |accessdate=2 May 2020 |work=[[Al Jazeera]] |date=1 May 2020 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20200502020549/https://www.aljazeera.com/news/2020/05/malaysia-detains-migrants-refugees-coronavirus-lockdown-200501134602431.html |archivedate=2 May 2020}}</ref>\n\n===2 May===\nThe Indian Government has extended the country's coronavirus lockdown by two weeks.<ref name=\"Al Jazeera 2 May reports\" />\n\nThe [[United Nations]] in Malaysia's Head of Communications and Advocacy, Ahmad Hafiz Osman, called for migrants, refugees, asylum seekers, and stateless individuals in Malaysia to have access to health services and services without fear of repercussions.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Nur |first1=Alisha |title=UN Malaysia voices concern over large-scale arrests of undocumented migrants in KL |url=https://www.thesundaily.my/local/un-malaysia-voices-concern-over-large-scale-arrests-of-undocumented-migrants-in-kl-FE2363205#pk_campaign=MASwpn&pk_kwd=UN+Malaysia+voices+concern+over+large-scale+arrests+of+undocumented+migrants+in+KL |accessdate=2 May 2020 |work=[[The Sun (Malaysia)|The Sun]] |date=2 May 2020 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20200502093020/https://www.thesundaily.my/local/un-malaysia-voices-concern-over-large-scale-arrests-of-undocumented-migrants-in-kl-FE2363205 |archivedate=2 May 2020}}</ref>\n\n[[Minister for Health (Singapore)|Health Minister]] [[Gan Kim Yong]] has announced that Singapore will lessen restrictions including allowing some businesses to resume operations on 12 May and that some students will be allowed to return to school from 19 May.<ref name=\"Al Jazeera 2 May reports\" />\n\n===4 May===\nThe Indian Government has indicated that it will ease lockdown restrictions although the nationwide lockdown will remain in force until 17 May. The Indian government has also colour-coded states and cities into red, orange, and green zones based on the number of cases. In red areas, businesses can operate at one-third capacity, construction can resume provided workers have onsite accommodation, and standalone shops can reopen. In orange zones, taxis are allowed to operate. In green zones, businesses can resume all activities unless they are prohibited under the national lockdown. At the national level, all travel remains suspended while all schools, shopping malls, hotels, and public spaces remain closed.<ref name=\"Al Jazeera 4 May reports\" />\n\nThe Malaysian federal government has allowed businesses including restaurants to reopen but they must adhere to social distancing, hygiene, and contact tracing requirements. Due to a spike of cases over the weekends, some state governments have indicated that they will not ease restrictions.<ref name=\"Al Jazeera 4 May reports\" />\n\n== Reactions and measures in Western Pacific ==\n===1 May===\n[[Prime Minister of Australia|Australian Prime Minister]] [[Scott Morrison]] has announced that the Australian Government will make a decision by next Friday (8 May) on whether to relax lockdown movement restrictions. Morrison also described Australia's [[Australia\u2013China relations|relations]] with China as mutually beneficial in the face of tensions over Canberra seeking an international inquiry into China's handling of the COVID-19 pandemic in [[Wuhan]]. Later, Morrison stated at a press conference that he had no evidence to suggest that the coronavirus originated in a Wuhan laboratory.<ref name=\"Al Jazeera 1 May reports\" />\n\nChinese authorities announced that they will be reopening Beijing's Palace Museum on 1 May. [[Hubei]] provincial authorities have announced that the province will lower its emergency response level from highest to second highest on 2 April.<ref name=\"Al Jazeera 1 May reports\" />\n\n[[Prime Minister of Japan|Japanese Prime Minister]] [[Shinzo Abe]] announced that the Japanese Government would decide by Monday (4 May) whether to extend the country's state of emergency, which is set to expire on 6 May.<ref name=\"Al Jazeera 1 May reports\" />\n\nThe Philippines Government has relaxed coronavirus restrictions by placing areas with fewer cases under a more relaxed quarantine; allowing work, public transport and businesses to resume operations at a reduced capacity.<ref name=\"Al Jazeera 1 May reports\" />\n\nAccording to figures released by the South Korean [[Ministry of Trade, Industry and Energy (South Korea)|Ministry of Trade, Industry and Energy]], South Korean exports declined by 24.3 percent in April 2020.<ref name=\"Al Jazeera 1 May reports\" />\n\n[[World Health Organization]] spokesperson [[Tarik Jasarevic]] has stated that the international organisation is seeking an invitation from China to participate in investigations into the animal origins of the coronavirus.<ref name=\"Al Jazeera 1 May reports\" />\n\n===2 May===\nThe [[Japan Sumo Association]] has announced that it will reconsider rescheduling its grand summer tournament scheduled for 24 May if the Japanese Government decides to extend the nationwide lockdown, which is scheduled to end on 6 May.<ref name=\"Al Jazeera 2 May reports\" />\n<ref name=\"Al Jazeera 2 May reports\" />\n\nIn the Philippines, Associate Justice of the [[Supreme Court of the Philippines|Supreme Court]] [[Marvic Leonen]] has confirmed that the Philippines Government has released 9,731 prisoners, mainly those awaiting trial who could not afford bail, in an effort to ease the spread of the coronavirus in the country's overcrowded prison system.<ref name=\"Al Jazeera 2 May reports\" />\n\n===3 May===\nThe Philippines has banned incoming flights for one week to curb the spread of the coronavirus. 20,000 repatriated Filipinos are undergoing mandatory quarantine.<ref name=\"Al Jazeera 3 May reports\" />\n\nThailand has eased restrictions on restaurants, hair salons and outdoor markets as long as they adhere to social distancing rules and conduct temperature tests.<ref name=\"Al Jazeera 3 May reports\" />\n\n[[Prime Minister of South Korea|South Korean Prime Minister]] [[Chung Sye-Kyun]] has announced that the country will ease social distancing restrictions, allowing businesses to reopen and allow public gatherings to take place provided they follow disinfection guidelines.<ref name=\"Al Jazeera 3 May reports\" />\n\n===4 May===\nIn Australia, the state New South Wales has begun opening schools on a staggered basis as part of a process of easing lockdown restrictions. [[Premier of New South Wales|New South Wales Premier]] [[Gladys Berejiklian]] confirmed that a seven year old boy had tested positive for the coronavirus, prompting the closure of his school. Meanwhile, Victoria state has asked parents to keep their children at home until the middle of the year.<ref name=\"Al Jazeera 4 May reports\" />\n\nThe [[Associated Press]] has reported that United States intelligence officials believed that China covered up the extent of the coronavirus outbreak in order to stock up on medical supplies needed to respond to it, citing a four-page [[United States Department of Homeland Security|Department of Homeland Security]] report dating back to 1 May.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Weisert |first1=Will |title=DHS report: China hid virus\u2019 severity to hoard supplies |url=https://apnews.com/bf685dcf52125be54e030834ab7062a8 |accessdate=4 May 2020 |agency=[[Associated Press]] |date=4 May 2020}}</ref>\n\nJapanese Economy Minister [[Yasutoshi Nishimura]] has announced that the Japanese Government is seeking to extend the country's nationwide state of emergency until 31 May. The government's state of emergency is due to expire on 6 May (Wednesday).<ref name=\"Al Jazeera 4 May reports\" />\n\n[[Prime Minister of New Zealand|New Zealand Prime Minister]] [[Jacinda Ardern]] has accepted an invitation from Australian Prime Minister Scott Morrison to participate in a meeting of Australia's emergency cabinet on Tuesday via video conference. Topics including the possible creation of an Australian-New Zealand travel bubble.<ref name=\"Al Jazeera 4 May reports\" />\n\nThe South Korean [[Ministry of Education (South Korea)|Education Minister]] [[Yoo Eun-hae]] has announced that the South Korean Government will reopen schools in stages from 13 May. She also indicated that schools may switch to online learning if a student contracts COVID-19.<ref name=\"Al Jazeera 4 May reports\" />\n\n[[FINA]] (the International Swimming Federation) has postponed the [[2021 World Aquatics Championships]], scheduled to be held in [[Fukuoka]], Japan in May 2021 to 13\u201329 May 2022.<ref name=\"Al Jazeera 4 May reports\" />\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Responses to the COVID-19 pandemic in February 2020]]\n* [[Responses to the COVID-19 pandemic in March 2020]]\n* [[Responses to the COVID-19 pandemic in April 2020]]\n* [[Timeline of the COVID-19 pandemic from November to December 2019]]\n* [[Timeline of the COVID-19 pandemic in January 2020]]\n* [[Timeline of the COVID-19 pandemic in February 2020]]\n* [[Timeline of the COVID-19 pandemic in March 2020]]\n* [[Timeline of the COVID-19 pandemic in April 2020]]\n* [[Timeline of the COVID-19 pandemic in May 2020]]\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|timeline}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Responses to the 2019-20 coronavirus pandemic in May 2020}}\n[[Category:May 2020 events]]\n[[Category:Timeline of the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|*2020-05]]\n[[Category:Responses to the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|*2020-05]]\n[[Category:Timelines of current events|coronavirus pandemic]]\n", "name_user": "Anonymous Random Person", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200e3 May:Spelling/grammar/punctuation/typographical correction", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Responses_to_the_COVID-19_pandemic_in_May_2020"}
